          <strong>Unit size</strong> is the obvious factor — larger units cost more. But <strong>construction quality</strong> matters just as much. An all-steel shipping container costs more to purchase than a wood-frame building, but it provides genuine rodent protection, fire resistance, and weather sealing that traditional storage does not. At Fort Knox, you get steel-container quality at prices competitive with (or lower than) basic wood-frame facilities.
        </p>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 18px;">
          <strong>Hidden fees</strong> are the biggest trap in storage pricing. A facility advertising "from $99/month" may add $30–$50 in admin fees, required insurance, lock purchases, and deposit charges at signing. Fort Knox publishes all-inclusive pricing — $130 or $230 — with zero add-ons. The price James quotes on the phone is the price you pay.
        </p>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">
          <strong>Seasonal demand</strong> also plays a role. Oil field activity in the Uintah Basin creates fluctuating storage demand. Fort Knox maintains consistent pricing year-round — no surge pricing during busy seasons.
        </p>
      </div>
